"Abstract Almost everyone agrees, including the legal profession, that courts are bursting at the seams from large caseloads; that delays and increased expenses must be expected by clients; and that traditional litigation may not be able to handle technology oriented cases these days. Technology related disputes are often more difficult to resolve because of the fact and law issues presented. Thus, these cases routinely also involve not only serious delays waiting for court dates, but also tremendous impact on usual work while parties and counsel prepare for trial. Ask any client who has been involved in major commercial litigation and they will tell you, it is virtually impossible to accomplish anything else while a big case is pending. Alternate means of resolving disputes (“ADR”) is arousing increasing interest among lawyers and their clients. This article describes some of the ADR trends and how practitioners can consider mediation (and other ADR methods) as a practical choice in appropriate cases."
